  },
  "learningOutcomes": [
    "Identify and label the major organelles of a plant and animal cell.",
    "Explain the specific function of mitochondria, chloroplasts, ER, Golgi apparatus, lysosomes, and vacuoles.",
    "Differentiate between plant and animal cells based on structural features."
  ],
  "introduction": "**The Mystery Factory**: \"Imagine you are a tiny worker inside your own body. You enter a bustling factory where thousands of workers (organelles) are busy making products, generating power, and cleaning up waste. If the 'power plant' stops working, what happens to the city? Today, we will tour this microscopic factory—the Cell—and discover how each organelle keeps life running!\"",
  "theory": {
    "overview": "Eukaryotic cells are complex structures containing membrane-bound organelles that perform specialized functions. These include energy producers (mitochondria/chloroplasts), production lines (ER/Golgi), and waste management systems (lysosomes).",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Mitochondria generate ATP through cellular respiration.",
      "Chloroplasts conduct photosynthesis in plant cells only.",
      "The Endomembrane system (ER, Golgi) handles protein/lipid synthesis and transport."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "Cells are not just bags of fluid; they are highly organized. The **Mitochondria** have a double membrane with inner folds called cristae to increase surface area for energy production. They contain their own DNA, suggesting an ancient evolutionary origin. In plants, the **Chloroplast** captures light energy using chlorophyll within thylakoids (stacked as grana) and converts it into glucose in the stroma.\n\nThe **Endoplasmic Reticulum (ER)** is a continuous membrane system. The Rough ER is studded with ribosomes for protein synthesis, while Smooth ER lacks them and focuses on lipid production and detoxification. These products are sent to the **Golgi Apparatus**, which modifies and packages them into vesicles for transport outside or inside the cell.\n\n**Lysosomes** act as the recycling center, using enzymes to break down waste. Finally, the distinction between plant and animal cells lies in the presence of a rigid **Cell Wall** (cellulose), **Chloroplasts**, and a large central **Vacuole** in plants, which provide structural support and storage."
  },
